|}

The first body excavated had red hair; this led to the nickname of "Ginger" by curators and later by the public.<ref name=bmdb/><ref name=auto-gt-2007 >{{citation | year=2007 | first=Cynthia Clayton |last=Ochterbeck| title=Michelin Green Guide Great Britain | edition=5 | publisher=Michelin Apa Publications | isbn=978-1-906261-08-5 | page=327 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jalf4tSUb68C }}</ref><ref name=dailymail>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-417396/Hi-Mummy-Im-home.html |title=Hi Mummy I'm home |work=Daily Mail |location=UK |first=Robert |last=Hardman|date=20 November 2006 |accessdate=4 June 2010}}</ref> After the [[Human Tissue Act 2004]], the British Museum has developed policies for ethical treatment of human remains and no longer uses this nickname.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/the_museum/news_and_press_releases/statements/human_remains.aspx |title=Human remains |publisher=British Museum |accessdate=15 June 2010 |archivedate=14 November 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5uFCXvc62?url=http://www.britishmuseum.org/the_museum/news_and_press_releases/statements/human_remains.aspx |deadurl=yes |df=dmy }}</ref>

===Death of Gebelein Man===
In November 2012 it was revealed that EA 32751 (Gebelein Man) had probably been murdered. A CAT scan of the mummified body taken at the [[Cromwell Hospital]] in London showed that Gebelein Man was aged about 18 to 20 at the time of his death and was well-muscled. Under his left shoulder blade, the scan revealed a puncture to the body; the murder weapon was used with such force that it slightly damaged the shoulder blade, but shattered the rib beneath it and penetrated the lung. It was believed that the injury was caused by a copper blade or flint knife at least 12&nbsp;cm in length and 2&nbsp;cm wide. Daniel Antoine, the [[British Museum]]'s expert on human remains, believes that Gebelein Man had been taken by surprise by the attack as there were no defense wounds.<ref>''[[The Times]]'' 16 November 2012 (pg 10)</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-20353934|title=British Museum exhibit Gebelein Man died 'violent death'|date=16 November 2012|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>

==Exhibition history==
[[File:Ginger (mummy) 1920.png|thumb|left|220px|upright|alt=1920's book plate of mummified body on display|Plate from ''By Nile and Tigris''<ref name=budge1920/> vol.2, 1920 (facing&nbsp;p.360) showing how the body (EA 32751) was displayed in the British Museum at that time.]]
The mummies were acquired by the [[British Museum]] in 1900.<ref>The registration number ''1900,1018.1'' shows the body logged as received on 18 October 1900.</ref> One male adult body, museum number EA 32751 (then nicknamed "Ginger"), went on display in 1901, and  was the earliest mummified body seen by the public. Apart from maintenance, it has been on continuous display in the same gallery since 1901.<ref name=CS134408841 >{{Cite news|title=Egyptian Antiquities At The British Museum |date=9 April 1902 |page=8 |url=http://archive.timesonline.co.uk/tol/keywordsearch.arc?queryKeywords=Egyptian+Antiquities+At+The+British+Museum |work=The Times |location=UK}}</ref><ref name=gu1987/> In 1987 the body was temporarily taken off display for restoration and a female mummified body replaced it. She was nicknamed "Gingerella" even though the body has long brown hair.<ref name=gu1987>{{Cite news|newspaper=The Guardian (London)|date=14 October 1987|title=Ancient Egyptian given new lease of life |first=Maev|last=Kennedy}}</ref><ref name=gingerella/><ref>{{Cite news|newspaper=The Associated Press|date=9 October 1987|title=British Museum Overhauls Popular Mummy}}</ref>

The male body, EA 32751,  is displayed in a reconstructed sand grave in the British Museum in room 64 and case 15. Though Budge wrote of "pots and flints" with the body, these artefacts were not acquired by the museum. A number of Egyptian grave goods taken from similar graves of the period are instead used in the display.<ref name=bmover>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/aes/p/predynastic_egyptian_man.aspx |title=Predynastic Egyptian Man (highlights) |publisher=British Museum |date=14 May 2010 |accessdate=4 June 2010}}</ref><ref name=bmdb/> The grave goods include black-topped clay pots that were typical of the predynastic period through to [[Naqada II]], and plain and buff coloured pots and bowls typical of slightly later periods. There are also slate palettes, hard stone vessels and flint knives which would be associated with more elaborate burials of the [[historical period]].<ref>{{harvnb|Strudwick|2006|p=26}}</ref>

{{quotation|One man was wrapped in a skin, a second in a mat of palm fibre, and the third was rolled up in a reed mat. The woman was without covering, and the only pot in her grave contained what seemed to be a sort of dried porridge...<br>
I unpacked the first man we had taken out of his grave at [[Gebel&ecirc;n]] one Saturday in March 1900, in the presence of [[David Lindsay, 27th Earl of Crawford|Lord Crawford]] and the Principal Librarian, and when it was laid on a table it was as complete as when I first saw it at Gebel&ecirc;n. But when it was examined again on the following Monday morning it was discovered that the top joint of one of the forefingers was missing, and it has, to my knowledge never been found since. The body was exhibited at once in the First Egyptian Room, and for the first time the British public saw a neolithic Egyptian.|[[E. A. Wallis Budge|Wallis Budge]]|By Nile and Tigris, 1920<ref name=budge1920>{{harvnb|Budge|1920}}</ref>}}

Of the other five bodies, only the female adult, given museum number EA 32752, has been exhibited.  In 1997-8 the body was part of a tour to Rome as part of the [[List of palazzi in Italy#Rome and Vatican City|Palazzo Ruspoli]], ''Ancient Faces'' exhibition.  Again in 2001 the body went to Birmingham as part of the [[Birmingham Museum & Art Gallery|Gas Hall]] ''Egypt Revealed'' exhibition.<ref name=gingerella>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/search_object_details.aspx?objectid=125758&partid=1 |title=Human mummy EA 32752 (collection database record) |publisher=British Museum |date=24 April 2001 |accessdate=12 June 2010}}</ref> In 2001, before going out on loan, the body had some restoration using [[Japanese tissue|Japanese kozo paper]] to secure a loose finger, reattach a rib and reattach some locks of hair. Strips of [[polyethylene]] were used to reduce movement of the right arm.<ref name=gingerella/>

